50|$|Between the Renaissance and the 16th century, {{actors and}} playwrights took upon {{themselves}} {{the handling of}} finances, general directorial duties, and stage management. Stage management first emerged as a distinct role in the 17th century during Shakespeare's and Molière's time, though it wasn't until the 18th century in England that <b>the</b> term <b>Stage</b> <b>Manager</b> was used. This {{was the first time}} a person other than actors and playwright was hired to direct or manage <b>the</b> <b>stage.</b> Over time, with the rise in complexity of theatre due to advances such as mechanized scenery, quick costume changes, and controlled lighting, <b>the</b> <b>stage</b> <b>manager's</b> job was split into two positions—director and <b>stage</b> <b>manager.</b>|$|R
